    complement: "This is the warmth-and-sparkle pair. Both are social, both are generous with their energy, both light up rooms. But they light up rooms differently. The Golden Retriever lights a room through warmth — people feel safe, welcomed, included. The Disco Ball lights a room through spectacle — people feel entertained, excited, part of something. Together, they create a social atmosphere that is both safe and thrilling, which is the rarest combination.\n\nThe Golden Retriever gives the Disco Ball something they secretly crave: stable warmth. The Disco Ball's social world is built on performance — they are loved for what they project, not for who they are. The Golden Retriever does not care about the projection. They love the person behind the sparkle, and they love them consistently, whether the Disco Ball is shimmering or dim. This consistency is disorienting for the Disco Ball, who has built their entire identity on being dazzling. Being loved while dim is a revelation.\n\nIn return, the Disco Ball gives the Golden Retriever something they secretly need: permission to shine. The Golden Retriever's warmth is generous but self-effacing — they shine the light on others, never on themselves. The Disco Ball's energy is contagious, and under its influence, the Golden Retriever discovers that they can be the center of attention without being selfish. The Disco Ball says 'you are amazing' and the Golden Retriever, for once, believes it. Not because the compliment is more skilled, but because the Disco Ball's conviction is total.",
    friction: "Both need validation, but from different sources. The Golden Retriever needs validation through connection — being included, being chosen, being told they matter. The Disco Ball needs validation through attention — being watched, being applauded, being the center. When they socialize together, the Golden Retriever will work the room making sure everyone is comfortable. The Disco Ball will work the room making sure everyone is entertained. Both are working. Neither is receiving. They go home together, exhausted, having given everything to the room and nothing to each other.\n\nThe loyalty gap is the deeper fracture. The Golden Retriever is loyal by instinct — they commit instantly and stay committed. The Disco Ball is loyal by circumstance — they stay as long as the light is good. When the Golden Retriever is not the most exciting person in the room, the Disco Ball may drift toward whoever is. This is not betrayal in the Disco Ball's mind — they are following the energy. But the Golden Retriever experiences it as abandonment. 'I was right here. You chose the brighter light.'\n\nThe crash mismatch is painful. The Disco Ball crashes hard after high-energy periods — going dark, withdrawing, becoming unreachable. The Golden Retriever's response to withdrawal is to chase — more warmth, more attention, more effort. But chasing a crashed Disco Ball does not help. It makes the crash worse. The Golden Retriever cannot understand why their warmth is not working, because warmth has always worked before. The Disco Ball cannot explain that the crash is not about the Golden Retriever, because the crash is not about anything — it is chemical, existential, and immune to love.",
