    complement: "This is the heart-and-grid pair. The Golden Retriever brings emotional abundance — warmth, loyalty, enthusiasm, the willingness to love without a cost-benefit analysis. The Spreadsheet brings structural abundance — organization, planning, reliability, the willingness to build systems that last. Together, they are the couple whose life works: the bills are paid, the birthdays are remembered, the love is real, and somehow there is a spreadsheet for all of it.\n\nThe Golden Retriever gives the Spreadsheet something they cannot generate: warmth that is not optimized. The Spreadsheet approaches everything systematically, including relationships — they show care through planning, through remembering, through being reliable. But reliability is not the same as warmth, and the Spreadsheet knows it. The Golden Retriever loves messily, impulsively, without a system. Watching the Golden Retriever love without calculating teaches the Spreadsheet that some things are better ungoverned. Not everything needs a column.\n\nIn return, the Spreadsheet gives the Golden Retriever something they desperately need: a structure that catches what their enthusiasm drops. The Golden Retriover promises everything, remembers half of it, and feels terrible about the gap. The Spreadsheet closes the gap silently — the reservation is made, the gift is ordered, the calendar is updated. The Golden Retriever provides the love. The Spreadsheet provides the infrastructure. The Golden Retriever never has to feel the weight of their own chaos because the Spreadsheet has already organized it into something manageable.",
    friction: "The Golden Retriever will express love spontaneously. The Spreadsheet will express love systematically. The Golden Retriever will bring home flowers for no reason. The Spreadsheet will have already ordered flowers on a recurring schedule. The Golden Retriever's gesture feels redundant. The Spreadsheet's gesture feels mechanical. Neither feels seen.\n\nThe emotional sealing is the core problem. The Spreadsheet processes feelings internally and privately. The Golden Retriever processes feelings externally and immediately. When the Golden Retriever says 'talk to me,' the Spreadsheet hears 'perform your emotions for me.' When the Spreadsheet says 'I am fine,' the Golden Retriever hears 'I do not trust you with my feelings.' Both are wrong. The Spreadsheet is fine — genuinely, structurally fine. The Golden Retriever is not demanding performance — they are offering presence. But the gap between internal processing and external processing is wide, and neither type knows how to bridge it.\n\nThe planning conflict is constant. The Golden Retriever wants to be spontaneous. The Spreadsheet wants to plan. 'Let us just go' sounds like freedom to the Golden Retriever and like chaos to the Spreadsheet. 'Let us plan it out' sounds like care to the Spreadsheet and like a cage to the Golden Retriever. Every weekend is a negotiation between spontaneity and structure, and neither side can understand why the other is so attached to their way.",
