    friction: "The Swiss Army Knife will deviate from the plan. The Spreadsheet will update the plan. The Swiss Army Knife will deviate from the updated plan. The Spreadsheet will feel disrespected — the plan exists for a reason. The Swiss Army Knife will feel controlled — the deviation happened for a reason. Both are right. Neither can see the other's reason.\n\nThe rigidity-flexibility spectrum is the constant battlefield. The Spreadsheet believes that a good system prevents problems. The Swiss Army Knife believes that a good response solves problems. The Spreadsheet will spend three days building a system to prevent a problem that the Swiss Army Knife would have solved in three minutes. The Swiss Army Knife will solve a problem in three minutes that the Spreadsheet could have prevented with a system built in three days. Both approaches are valid. Both are infuriating to the other.\n\nThe identity problem echoes other pairs but has a unique flavor here. The Swiss Army Knife is what they do — their identity is in their adaptability. The Spreadsheet is how they organize — their identity is in their systems. When the Swiss Army Knife ignores a system, the Spreadsheet experiences it as a rejection of their self, not just their plan. When the Spreadsheet enforces a system, the Swiss Army Knife experiences it as a denial of their competence. The conflict is not about the system. It is about whether each person's way of being in the world is respected.",
