    friction: "The Swiss Army Knife will adapt to the Wildcard's chaos. The Wildcard will escalate the chaos to test the adaptation. This is a loop. The Swiss Army Knife's adaptability is not infinite — it has a ceiling, and the Wildcard is constitutionally incapable of not finding it. When the ceiling is reached, the Swiss Army Knife does not break gracefully. They snap. The Wildcard is surprised, because from their perspective, the Swiss Army Knife has always handled everything.\n\nThe disappearance problem is severe. The Wildcard ghosts — disappears for days, sometimes weeks, following an impulse that took them somewhere else. The Swiss Army Knife, whose instinct is to be useful, has nothing to be useful for when the Wildcard is gone. They cannot fix an absence. They cannot adapt to someone who is not there. The Swiss Army Knife's competence becomes irrelevant, and irrelevance is their deepest fear. The Wildcard returns to find the Swiss Army Knife distant and cannot understand why — they were only gone a few days.\n\nThe commitment question is the fracture line. The Swiss Army Knife commits through consistency — showing up, being reliable, being the person who is always there. The Wildcard commits through intensity — being fully present when they are present, and fully absent when they are not. The Swiss Army Knife cannot trust presence that might vanish. The Wildcard cannot trust consistency that feels like a cage. Both love. Neither recognizes the other's love as love.",
