    complement: "This is the do-and-rest pair. The Swiss Army Knife is always in motion — adapting, fixing, being useful. The Cozy Blanket is always at rest — warm, present, unhurried. Together, they represent the two states that every human needs: action and stillness. The Swiss Army Knife provides the action. The Cozy Blanket provides the stillness. Neither state is complete without the other.\n\nThe Swiss Army Knife gives the Cozy Blanket something they need but would never ask for: a reason to move. The Cozy Blanket's comfort can become inertia — not unhappy, but static. The Swiss Army Knife's energy is not aggressive. It is practical. They do not drag the Cozy Blanket into activity. They simply make activity look manageable. 'I am going to fix the shelf. Want to hold the tools?' is not a demand. It is an invitation that respects the Cozy Blanket's pace while expanding their world.\n\nIn return, the Cozy Blanket gives the Swiss Army Knife something they desperately need and never allow themselves: permission to stop. The Swiss Army Knife's identity is built on being useful. Stopping feels like failing. The Cozy Blanket does not demand usefulness. They do not need anything fixed. They are simply warm and present, and that presence creates a space where the Swiss Army Knife can set down the tools without feeling like they have abandoned their post. Being with the Cozy Blanket is the only time the Swiss Army Knife is not working. The relief is profound.",
    friction: "The Swiss Army Knife will fill every silence with usefulness. The Cozy Blanket will let them, because the Cozy Blanket does not mind activity. But the activity is not for the Cozy Blanket. It is for the Swiss Army Knife, who does not know how to exist without a task. The Cozy Blanket will eventually feel that the Swiss Army Knife is not present — they are just busy, and the busyness happens to be nearby.\n\nThe pace gap is constant. The Swiss Army Knife moves at practical speed — efficient, purposeful, always advancing. The Cozy Blanket moves at comfort speed — slow, meandering, present. The Swiss Army Knife will finish a task and look for the next one while the Cozy Blanket is still appreciating the first. The Swiss Army Knife interprets the Cozy Blanket's slowness as laziness. The Cozy Blanket interprets the Swiss Army Knife's speed as anxiety. Neither is entirely wrong.\n\nThe identity tension is the deepest fracture. The Swiss Army Knife is what they do. The Cozy Blanket is who they are. When the Swiss Army Knife asks 'what do you want to do today?' and the Cozy Blanket says 'nothing,' the Swiss Army Knife cannot compute. Nothing is not a task. Nothing cannot be optimized. The Swiss Army Knife will fill the nothing with something — a project, a plan, a fix — and the Cozy Blanket will watch their quiet morning disappear into the Swiss Army Knife's need to be useful. The Cozy Blanket does not protest. But the warmth dims.",
