    complement: "This is the chaos-and-calm pair. The Wildcard brings energy, unpredictability, and the constant possibility that today is the day everything changes. The Cozy Blanket brings stability, warmth, and the constant assurance that nothing has to change unless you want it to. Together, they are the pair that answers the question: can you have both adventure and home? Yes, but only if one person is the adventure and the other is the home.\n\nThe Wildcard gives the Cozy Blanket something they need but would never seek: stories. The Cozy Blanket's life, left to its own devices, is warm and uneventful. Not unhappy — just uniform. The Wildcard bursts through that uniformity with tales of impulse and chaos, and the Cozy Blanket, who would never live these stories, gets to hear them. This is not vicarious living. It is expansion. The Cozy Blanket's world gets bigger every time the Wildcard walks through the door with a new ridiculous story, and bigger worlds are better worlds, even if you never visit them yourself.\n\nIn return, the Cozy Blanket gives the Wildcard something they have never had: a home that does not require staying. Most homes come with expectations — be here, be reliable, be consistent. The Cozy Blanket's home comes with none of these. It is simply warm, simply present, simply there whenever the Wildcard returns. The Wildcard can leave for two weeks and come back to the same warmth, no lecture, no punishment, no guilt trip. This is disorienting for the Wildcard, who has internalized that leaving has a cost. The Cozy Blanket teaches them that some warmth does not charge interest.",
    friction: "The Wildcard will disrupt the Cozy Blanket's peace. This is not malicious — it is just what the Wildcard does. They arrive with energy, with chaos, with a plan that was made three minutes ago. The Cozy Blanket's calm is disturbed. Not destroyed — the Cozy Blanket is resilient — but disturbed. The Wildcard does not notice the disturbance because they are already in the next moment. The Cozy Blanket does not mention it because mentioning it would require more energy than the disturbance cost.\n\nThe ghosting problem is painful but different here. The Wildcard disappears. The Cozy Blanket does not spiral — they do not have the anxiety infrastructure for spiraling. They simply wait. The waiting is not anxious. It is quiet. But quiet waiting, over time, becomes a kind of resignation. The Cozy Blanket stops expecting the Wildcard to be present. They build a life that does not include the Wildcard, because the Wildcard is not there enough to include. When the Wildcard returns, they find a life that has moved on without them. The Cozy Blanket is warm. The warmth is no longer for them.\n\nThe intensity gap is the deepest tension. The Wildcard's life is high-variance — peaks and valleys, chaos and quiet, there and gone. The Cozy Blanket's life is low-variance — warm, steady, the same temperature every day. The Wildcard may start to feel that the Cozy Blanket is boring. The Cozy Blanket may start to feel that the Wildcard is exhausting. Neither is wrong. Neither is right. They are just on different wavelengths, and the gap between the wavelengths is the space where the relationship either finds its rhythm or loses its signal.",
